Meet Eddie Lampert's biggest fan


Edward Lampert has at least one fan in high finance these days. Vadim Perelman, 31, founder of Los Angeles-based hedge fund Baker Street Capital, first made news in September when he published a bullish report about Sears Holdings Corp.'s real estate portfolio. Yesterday, he increased his stake in the company to 10.8 percent, according to regulatory filings, lifting his holdings to 11.5 million shares and options.His 2 million shares are worth $93.4 million and his total holdings would be valued at almost $540 million assuming the options are priced at the same level as the stock. Baker Street now ranks as the eighth-largest investor in Sears, according to Bloomberg data. Regulatory filings indicate Baker Street owned 1.5 million shares of Sears common as of June 30, purchased in the second quarter and equivalent to a 1.4 percent interest. Mr. Lampert remains Sears' top stockholder, owning 48 percent of the Hoffman Estates-based department store chain.Mr. Perelman's report estimated that Sears' real estate is "conservatively worth" more than $8.6 billion — a 68 percent premium over the entire company's current market cap of $5.1 billion, at $46.86 a share. Some $7.3 billion, the equivalent to $69 a share, was attributed to Sears' top 350 owned stores and best 50 leases. The report garnered media attention, including two mentions in the Wall Street Journal, and Sears' stock climbed to a 52-week high of $67.50 less than two months after the report was published.Since then, one analyst has argued that Mr. Perelman's valuation of at least one property was too high. Chad Brand, founder of St. Louis-based Peridot Capital LLC, wrote that Mr. Perelman and Baker Street pegged Sears' lease at Toronto's Eaton Center as worth $590 million. But less than two months later, Sears decided to sell the lease, along with four others, back to the landlord for a total of $400 million.As Mr. Brand wrote in a blog post: "Even if you assume Eaton Center was by far the most valuable of the five stores (let's say $300 million versus $25 million each for the other four), Baker Street likely overestimated its value by 100 percent."Mr. Perelman, reached by phone last night, fired back, saying that the $590 million number was simply "illustrative" and that Sears Canada property was not figured into his report's formal $8.6 billion valuation. Moreover, he pointed out that the Eaton Center sale was only for about half of the property — Sears handed over the first four floors and kept floors five through eight — meaning that the property's total value was closer to his estimate than Mr. Brand asserted. Mr. Perelman remains adamant that Sears is a great value right now. Most other analysts have valued Sears at $20 to $55 a share; Mr. Perelman said he stands behind his estimate that shares are worth $92 to $169. "We clearly love the investment and we clearly added to it," Mr. Perelman said. "We think people completely misunderstand and underestimate Eddie.""We think the margin of safety here is better than anything we've found in the public markets," he continued. "We feel the extent to which everyone has focused on negative same-store sales is very myopic."In October, Barron's studied Baker Street's stake (see bottom of page) in Sears, noting that it had purchased call options on 7 million Sears shares in January. According to an expert who ran the numbers, Baker Street's position will produce a profit only if Sears stock trades above $60 during the options' two-year contract.Sears stock closed yesterday at $46.86, down nearly 2 percent.


Sears Holdings Corp.
Edward Lampert
